LGIA CO-TENANCY AGREEMENT
This LGIA CO-TENANCY AGREEMENT (this "Agreement") is made and entered into as of July 1, 2022, by and between IP Oberon, LLC, a Delaware limited liability company ("Oberon"), in its individual capacity, IP Oberon II, LLC, a Delaware limited liability company ("Oberon II"), and IP Oberon BESS, LLC, a Delaware limited liability company ("Oberon BESS" and, together with Oberon and Oberon II, each individually a "Co-Tenant" and collectively the "Co-Tenants"), and Oberon in its capacity as Manager hereunder. RECITALS A. The Co-Tenants are developing and will construct, own and operate a series of solar energy and energy storage projects with an aggregate Generating Facility Capacity (as defined herein) of 500 MW and an aggregate Charging Capacity of 530.93 MW (as defined herein) located in Riverside County, California in the approximate locations shown on Exhibit A attached hereto. B. Each Co-Tenant will construct, own and operate its respective Project (as defined herein), including photovoltaic panels, one or more battery energy storage systems ("BESS"), current inverters and other assets, but will jointly own and share, the rights and obligations under the LGIA (as defined herein), as tenants in common. C. The Co-Tenants, as tenants-in-common, have entered into that certain Large Generator Interconnection Agreement by and between the Co-Tenants, Southern California Edison Company ("SCE") and the California Independent System Operator Corporation (the "CAISO"), dated as of April 27, 2021, as may be further amended from time-to-time, together with all agreements, schedules, appendices, exhibits and other documents ancillary thereto (the "LGIA") for the purpose of securing interconnection rights for each of the Projects. D. The Co-Tenants, as tenants-in-common, among themselves and other entities, hold or anticipate holding undivided interests in and to certain facilities, including a generator tie-line, switchyard and related facilities (the "Shared Facilities"), pursuant to a separate agreement (the "Shared Facilities Agreement") to be entered into by and between the Co-Tenants and other entities. E. The Co-Tenants desire to enter into this Agreement to set forth the terms and conditions under which they will be co-tenants under the LGIA and share the LGIA between themselves and their Projects, to designate Oberon as the "Manager" under the LGIA in order to administer and manage the Co-Tenants' rights and obligations under the LGIA with respect to CAISO and the Participating TO, and certain other related matters. NOW, THEREFORE, in consideration of the foregoing and the agreements and covenants contained herein, and other good and valuable consideration, the receipt and sufficiency of which are hereby acknowledged, the Parties hereto agree as follows: AGREEMENT ARTICLE I DEFINITIONS 1.1 Certain Definitions . Capitalized words and phrases used herein shall have the following meanings, or the meanings given in the Sections of this Agreement in which they are defined, unless the text expressly or by necessary implication requires otherwise. "Affiliate" means, with respect to a Person, any other Person that, directly or indirectly through one or more intermediaries, Controls, is Controlled by or is under common Control with such first Person. "Agreement" has the meaning given in the preamble to this Agreement, and includes all exhibits and appendices hereto. "Applicable Laws and Regulations" has the meaning given in the LGIA. "Arbitration Rules" has the meaning given forth in Section 5.4(a). "Business Day" means any day other than a Saturday, Sunday, legal holiday or day when banks in either New York, New York or San Francisco, California are required or authorized to be closed. "Bankruptcy Event" means, with respect to any Party, such Party: (i) voluntarily files a petition or otherwise commences, authorizes or acquiesces in the commencement of a proceeding or cause of action under any bankruptcy, insolvency, reorganization or similar law, or has any such petition filed or commenced against it by its creditors and such petition is not dismissed within sixty (60) days of the filing or commencement or an order for relief is entered; (ii) makes an assignment or any general arrangement for the benefit of creditors; (iii) otherwise becomes insolvent, however evidenced; (iv) has a liquidator, administrator, receiver, trustee, conservator or similar official appointed with respect to it or any substantial portion of its property or assets; or (v) is generally unable to pay its debts as they fall due. "CAISO" has the meaning given in the recitals to this Agreement. "CAISO Controlled Grid" has the meaning given in the LGIA. "CAISO Tariff" shall mean the CAISO Fifth Replacement FERC Electric Tariff, including the Business Practice Manuals issued pursuant thereto, as they may be amended, supplemented or replaced (in whole or in part) from time to time. "Charging Capacity" has the meaning given in the LGIA. "Claims" has the meaning given in Section 2.7(a). "Control" means the possession, directly or indirectly, of the power to direct or cause the direction of the management or policies of a Person, whether through the ownership of voting securities, its capacity as sole or managing member, its capacity as general partner, by contract or otherwise. The term "Control" when used as a verb shall have a correlative meaning. "Co-Tenant" and "Co-Tenants" have the meanings given in the preamble to this Agreement. "Co-Tenant Representative" has the meaning given in Section 7.12. "Curtailed Output Cap" has the meaning given in Section 2.4(c)(iv). "Defaulting Party" has the meaning given in Section 5.1. "Demand" has the meaning given in Section 5.4(b). "Demanding Party" has the meaning given in Section 5.4(b). "Dispute" has the meaning given in Section 5.4(a). "Effective Date" shall be the date established by FERC in its order accepting the Agreement for filing. "Emergency Condition" has the meaning given in the LGIA. "Event of Default" has the meaning given in Section 5.1. "FERC" means the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission or any successor agency. "Financing Party" means any and all lenders (including the U.S. Department of Energy, as a loan guarantor, and the "owner lessor" or similar entity in a lease financing) providing senior or subordinated construction, interim or long-term debt financing or refinancing (including hedging counterparties) for the development, construction, purchase or operation of a Project and any trustee or agent acting on behalf of any such lenders; provided, however, that the Co-Tenants may agree by separate written agreement or instrument that another Person shall have the rights of a "Financing Party" hereunder. "Force Majeure" means (i) with respect to the LGIA and the Interconnection Facilities, "Force Majeure" as defined in the LGIA, and (ii) in all other cases, any act, casualty or occurrence, condition, event or circumstance of any kind or nature not reasonably within the excused party's control and which could not have been avoided by reasonable measures, including: (A) acts of God or the elements (including fire, earthquake, explosion, flood, epidemic or any other similar casualty or accident) or condemnation; (B) strikes, lock outs or other labor disputes (unless the strike, lock out or labor dispute is directed solely against the party claiming the Force Majeure); (C) the failure or inability to obtain permits and other governmental authorizations for reasons not within the excused party's control and which could not have been avoided by reasonable measures; and (D) war, terrorism, sabotage, civil strife or other violence. Force Majeure expressly does not include late delivery or breakage of equipment or materials or economic hardship except to the extent caused by a Force Majeure event. "FPA" has the meaning given in Section 2.9(a). "Full Capacity Deliverability Status" has the meaning given in the CAISO Tariff. "General Default Cure Period" has the meaning given in Section 5.1(b). "Generating Facility Capacity" has the meaning given in the LGIA. "Good Utility Practice" has the meaning given in the LGIA. "Income Tax Component of Contribution" or "ITCC" has the meaning given in the LGIA. "Indemnified Co-Tenant" has the meaning given in Section 2.7(a). "Indemnifying Co-Tenant" has the meaning given in Section 2.7(a). "Interconnection Customer" has the meaning given in the LGIA. "Interconnection Customer's Interconnection Facilities" has the meaning given in the LGIA. "Interconnection Facilities" has the meaning given in the LGIA. "Interconnection Facilities Charge" has the meaning given in the LGIA. "Interest Rate" means the lesser of (a) the prime rate as published in "The Money Rates" Section of The Wall Street Journal (U.S. Edition), plus five percent (5%) per annum and (b) the highest rate permitted under Applicable Laws and Regulations. "LGIA" has the meaning given in the recitals to this Agreement. "LGIA Costs" means (i) all amounts payable to CAISO or the Participating TO relating to ongoing costs associated with the Interconnection Facilities and Network Upgrades, including the Interconnection Facilities Charge, and (ii) all costs and expenses necessary or appropriate for the Manager to incur or pay in connection with administering and managing the LGIA, including in connection with affirmative covenants with respect to maintenance of the Interconnection Customer's Interconnection Facilities, communications with CAISO, insurance and reporting, and compliance with applicable NERC and regional entity reliability standards; provided, that, LGIA Costs shall not include the cost of construction of Interconnection Facilities and Network Upgrades or the ITCC. "Manager" means initially Oberon, in its capacity as "Manager" under the LGIA, any subsequent Person appointed as Manager pursuant to this Agreement, and their respective successors and permitted assigns. "Manager Representative" has the meaning given in Section 7.13. "Maximum Capacity" means, in respect of the Oberon Project, a solar generation and battery energy storage facility with a net generating capacity of approximately 250 MWac and a Charging Capacity of 132.74 MW, in respect of the Oberon II Project, a solar generation and battery energy storage facility with a net generating capacity of approximately 250 MWac and a Charging Capacity of 132.73 MWac, and, in respect of the Oberon BESS Project, a battery energy storage facility with a net discharging capacity of approximately 250 MWac and a Charging Capacity of 265.46 MWac; provided, that the Maximum Capacity of each Project shall be limited in accordance with the Shared Facilities Agreement such that, when combined with the Maximum Capacities of the other Projects, the aggregate Maximum Capacities of the solar generation facilities shall not exceed, at any time, the Generating Facility Capacity, which is 500 MWac as measured at the Point of Interconnection, and the aggregate Charging Capacity of the battery energy storage facilities shall not exceed, at any time, 530.93 MWac, as identified and described in Appendix C to the LGIA, and summarized on Exhibit B, which Maximum Capacity may be changed only in accordance with Section 2.6. Without prejudice to the immediately preceding sentence, a Project's nameplate or nominal capacity may be greater than its Maximum Capacity. "MWac" means a megawatt or megawatts AC, as the context may require. "NERC" means the North American Electric Reliability Corporation or its successor organization. "Net Qualifying Capacity" shall have the meaning set forth in the CAISO Tariff. "Network Upgrades" has the meaning given in the LGIA. "Oberon" has the meaning given in the preamble to this Agreement. "Oberon Project" means the solar energy electric generating facility and energy storage facility to be developed, owned and operated by Oberon (or its successor or permitted assign) with a Generating Facility Capacity of 250 MWac and a Charging Capacity of 132.74 MWac, in the approximate location shown on Exhibit A attached hereto. "Oberon II" has the meaning given in the preamble to this Agreement. "Oberon II Project" means the solar energy electric generating facility and energy storage facility to be developed, owned and operated by Oberon II (or its successor or permitted assign) with a Generating Facility Capacity of 250 MWac and a Charging Capacity of 132.73 MWac, in the approximate location shown on Exhibit A attached hereto. "Oberon BESS" has the meaning given in the preamble to this Agreement. "Oberon BESS Project" means the battery energy storage system to be developed, owned and operated by Oberon BESS (or its successor or permitted assign) with a Generating Facility Capacity of 250 MWac and a Charging Capacity of 265.46 MW, in the approximate location shown on Exhibit A attached hereto. "Participating TO" has the meaning given in the LGIA. The Parties agree that the Participating TO is SCE. "Party" means any of the Co-Tenants or the Manager. "Payment Default Cure Period" has the meaning given in Section 5.1(a). "Percentage Interest" means, 33.34 percent (33.34%) with respect to Oberon, 33.33 percent (33.33%) with respect to Oberon II, and 33.33 percent (33.33%) with respect to Oberon BESS. "Person" means any individual or entity, and the heirs, personal representatives, successors and assigns of such individual or entity where the context so permits. "Point of Interconnection" has the meaning given in the LGIA. "Project" means each of the Oberon Project, the Oberon II Project, and the Oberon BESS Project. "Project Controlled Assets" means, for each Co-Tenant, any of the assets comprising its respective Project, the corresponding Project Real Property and related Project agreements and contractual arrangements. For the avoidance of doubt, the Project Controlled Assets exclude the LGIA. "Project Real Property" means, for any Project, the real property interests utilized by such Project. "SCE" has the meaning given in the recitals to this Agreement. "Shared Facilities" has the meaning given in the recitals to this Agreement. "Shared Facilities Agreement" has the meaning given in the recitals to this Agreement. "Shortfall" has the meaning given in Section 2.4(c)(iv). "Surrendering Co-Tenant" has the meaning given in Section 4.2. "Transfer" means, with respect to any asset, the sale, assignment, transfer, pledge, encumbrance, or other disposition of such asset. "Transferee" shall be interpreted accordingly. "Undivided Interest" has the meaning given in Section 2.1. "WECC" means the Western Electricity Coordinating Council or its successor organization.
1.2 Rules of Construction . Except where expressly provided or unless the context necessarily requires otherwise, (a) all references in this Agreement to a given Article, Section, Subsection, clause or Exhibit is a reference to an Article, Section, Subsection, clause or Exhibit of this Agreement, (b) the terms "hereof", "herein", "hereto", "hereunder" and "herewith" refer to this Agreement as a whole, (c) references in this Agreement to a given agreement, instrument, document or law is a reference to that agreement, instrument, document or law as modified, amended, supplemented and restated from time to time, (d) "includes" or "including" means "including without limitation", (e) references in this Agreement to "days" means calendar days unless Business Days are specified; and (f) all personal pronouns, whether masculine, feminine or neuter, include all other genders, the singular includes the plural, and the plural includes the singular. ARTICLE II CO-TENANCY RIGHTS AND OBLIGATIONS 2.1 Declaration of Intention . The Parties hereby declare that their relationship in and to the LGIA and the Interconnection Customer's rights and obligations thereunder is and will be that of tenants-in-common, and that each Co-Tenant will have an undivided interest ("Undivided Interest") in the LGIA and the Interconnection Customer's rights and obligations thereunder, expressly subject, however, to the terms, conditions, limitations and requirements set forth in this Agreement. Nothing contained in this Agreement will be deemed to constitute the Parties as partners or joint venturers. The Parties acknowledge and agree that the Oberon Project, the Oberon II Project, and the Oberon BESS Project will be treated as a single Project under the LGIA and that there can be no more than three (3) co-tenants under the LGIA without the consent of CAISO and the Participating TO. 2.2 Use of LGIA . The LGIA shall be held and used solely to permit the interconnection of the Projects to the CAISO Controlled Grid and to deliver electricity and electricity-related products generated or otherwise made available by the respective Projects owned by each Co-Tenant (or by such Co-Tenant's successors or permitted assigns) and to receive Charging Capacity at the Point of Interconnection. No Co-Tenant may use or permit the use of the LGIA in a manner that would reasonably be expected to interfere with the use and enjoyment by the other Co-Tenant of such Co-Tenant's Project, or to violate Applicable Laws and Regulations; provided that a Co-Tenant's use of the LGIA in compliance with this Agreement shall be deemed to not interfere with the other Co-Tenant's use and enjoyment of its Project. In the event of a conflict between the terms of the LGIA and this Agreement, the terms of the LGIA shall prevail. 2.3 Maximum Capacity . No Co-Tenant shall deliver energy from its respective Project to the Point of Interconnection to the extent a Co-Tenant's delivery of such energy from its respective Project causes such Co-Tenant to exceed its Maximum Capacity. No Co-Tenant shall receive Charging Capacity for its respective Project at the Point of Interconnection that cause such Co-Tenant to exceed its Maximum Capacity. To the extent that conditions exist which result in a Co-Tenant delivering energy to, or receive Charging Capacity from, the Point of Interconnection for its respective Project in excess of the Maximum Capacity in respect of such Project, then such Co-Tenant shall at its expense immediately curtail the operation of its Project so as not to exceed its Maximum Capacity. 2.4 Curtailment . (a) The Manager may, in accordance with this Section 2.4, direct the Co-Tenants to interrupt or reduce deliveries of electrical power (i) with the prior consent of all of the Co-Tenants (not including any Defaulting Party), when necessary in order to maintain, repair, replace, remove, investigate, inspect or test any part of any Project; (ii) if the Manager determines, in its reasonable discretion, that interruption or reduction is necessary due to an Emergency Condition; or (iii) at the direction of the Participating TO or the CAISO pursuant to rights under the LGIA. Manager will use commercially reasonable efforts to give the Co-Tenants as much advance notice as is reasonably possible for interruptions, reductions or curtailments under this clause (a). (b) With respect to any interruption or reduction of deliveries of electrical power pursuant to clauses (i) or (ii) of Section 2.4(a), the Manager shall limit the length and quantity of any such interruption or curtailment to the minimum extent and minimum time strictly necessary to correct the problem. Any interruption or curtailment made pursuant to clause (i) of Section 2.4(a) shall be made consistent with Good Utility Practice and to the extent commercially reasonable during periods of low or no solar generation or low energy prices.
(c) In the event of any curtailment of interconnection services at the direction of CAISO or Participating TO, subject to Section 2.4(d), such curtailment shall be allocated in the following manner until such curtailment is achieved:
(i) first, each Co-Tenant (if any) that is delivering energy in excess of such Co-Tenant's Maximum Capacity shall reduce deliveries down to such Co-Tenant's Maximum Capacity; (ii) second, each Co-Tenant that is delivering test power shall reduce all such deliveries down to zero; (iii) third, as provided in and to the extent applicable under Section 2.4(d)(ii) below, until all such curtailments have been applied or any or all Co-Tenants have been fully curtailed; and (iv) fourth, subject to Section 2.4(d)(i) below, to the extent it has not already been fully curtailed, each Co-Tenant shall reduce its energy deliveries so that they do not exceed an amount (the "Curtailed Output Cap") equal to (X) such Co-Tenant's Maximum Capacity, minus (Y) the product of (1) the aggregate number of MWac then required for the combined Projects to curtail (after application of preceding clause (i)) times (2) such Co-Tenant's Percentage Interest; provided, further, that if during any relevant period of curtailment any Co-Tenant is delivering energy at a level less than its Curtailed Output Cap (any such amount, a "Shortfall") either because such Co-Tenant's Project is undergoing maintenance, has a forced outage, or other circumstance, then for so long as such Shortfall exists, the Manager shall use reasonable efforts to authorize the other Co-Tenant to generate above such Co-Tenant's Curtailed Output Cap. (d) Notwithstanding the other provisions of this Section 2.4:
(i) The Manager shall curtail on a non-pro rata, but equitable and reasonable basis (as determined by the Manager in good faith) if (A) in spite of the Manager's good faith efforts to direct the Co-Tenants to comply with this Section 2.4, curtailment of interconnection services directed by the CAISO or Participating TO is not otherwise achievable, or (B) such non-pro rata allocation is otherwise necessary to comply with the LGIA or CAISO or Participating TO direction, and, in each of the foregoing clauses (A) and (B), that such non-pro rata allocation will not result in a default under the LGIA; and
(ii) To the extent that the need for any curtailment, interruption or reduction can be attributed to a particular Co-Tenant's Project or portions of its Project or the failure of such Project to comply with the order to curtail or a default by such Co-Tenant under the LGIA or an applicable power purchase agreement, or to the extent such Co-Tenant's Project is the cause of an Emergency Condition or is directed by CAISO or the Participating TO to curtail, then all such curtailment shall be allocated first to such Co-Tenant and such Co-Tenant will be responsible for all costs, liabilities, and damages resulting from such curtailment (subject to the limitations in this Agreement) and the Manager shall, to the extent possible, limit such interruption or reduction to such Project or such portions of the Project, as the case may be.
(e) Each Co-Tenant shall promptly effect such interruption in, or reduction of, delivery as the Manager shall direct pursuant to this Section 2.4 (with the prior consent of all of the Co-Tenants (not including any Defaulting Party), in the case of curtailments under Section 2.4(a)(i)) upon notice from the Manager. In the event notice is impracticable or a Co-Tenant fails to promptly comply therewith, the Manager may effect the same by direct action. A Co-Tenant that fails to implement any such curtailment, interruption or reduction, shall be responsible for all cost and expenses related thereto, including deviation or imbalance charges and penalties assessed by the CAISO.
2.5 Shared Expenses . Each Co-Tenant hereby confirms its obligation to share in the payment of all costs, charges and expenses incurred in connection with the LGIA in accordance with the following provisions including, without limitation, the cost of construction of Interconnection Facilities and Network Upgrades, the Income Tax Component of Contribution and all ongoing costs associated with such facilities, including the Interconnection Facilities Charge: (a) LGIA Costs. As between themselves (but without limiting each Co-Tenant's rights with regard to contributions from other entities under any other agreements, including the Shared Facilities Agreement), each Co-Tenant shall be responsible for the payment of its pro rata share of the LGIA Costs in proportion to such Co-Tenant's Percentage Interest; provided, that, Oberon has funded and will not seek reimbursement for amounts payable to CAISO or the Participating TO relating to the cost of construction of Interconnection Facilities and Network Upgrades. Such payment shall be paid when due to Manager, and Manager shall pay such amount to the applicable parties, unless Manager requests that each Co-Tenant pay any LGIA Costs due to CAISO or the Participating TO directly, in which case each Co-Tenant shall pay such LGIA Costs to CAISO and/or the Participating TO directly in proportion to such Co-Tenant's Percentage Interest. In either case, each Co-Tenant shall pay its share of LGIA Costs without regard to whether such Co-Tenant has issued a notice to proceed with construction of its Project prior to the date such payment is due to CAISO or the Participating TO. Notwithstanding anything to the contrary herein, any capital expenditures arising out of any equipment or facilities solely required to interconnect a particular Project shall be the sole responsibility of such Project and its Co-Tenant. (b) Collection and Payment of LGIA Costs. The Manager shall, as authorized representative for each Co-Tenant, administer the collection, payment and reimbursement of the LGIA Costs and other amounts relating to the performance of the Interconnection Customer's rights and obligations under the LGIA, including amounts due to or from the Interconnection Customer under or in connection with the LGIA. The Manager shall be responsible for invoicing the Co-Tenants their respective shares of such LGIA Costs and providing backup documentation for such invoices. The Manager shall establish procedures for invoicing and collecting payments from Co-Tenants in order to enable Manager to timely collect and pay for LGIA Costs and to enable Manager and Co-Tenants to achieve the payment requirements under and in connection with the LGIA. Each Co-Tenant shall have the right to audit, and receive periodic supporting documentation for, any expenses or other amounts required to be paid by such Co-Tenant hereunder. (c) ITCC Security. As among the Co-Tenants, Oberon shall maintain all security required under the LGIA to satisfy the Co-Tenants' joint ITCC tax liability. (d) To the extent that the Manager receives any damages, credits or refunds pursuant to the LGIA, the Manager shall promptly remit such damages, credits or refunds to the Co-Tenants according to each Co-Tenant's Percentage Interest (unless such damages, credits or refunds accrue to a specific Co-Tenant, in which event the Manager shall promptly remit them to such Co-Tenant); for the avoidance of doubt, any reimbursement of initial Network Upgrade costs funded by Oberon shall accrue only to Oberon and shall not be remitted to the Co-Tenants in accordance with their Percentage Interests. 2.6 Changes in Maximum Capacity . (a) The Maximum Capacity of any Project shall be increased only upon receipt by such Project's Co-Tenant of (i) written consent to such increase provided by the other Co-Tenant, such consent to be provided in each such Co-Tenant's sole discretion, (ii) all consents required under the Shared Facilities Agreement, (iii) an executed and effective new or amended LGIA that reflects the increase in Maximum Capacity and (iv) any other necessary consents by CAISO and the Participating TO; provided however, that any such increase in Maximum Capacity shall result in a proportionate increase in such Co-Tenant's responsibility for payment of Shared Expenses, including payment of LGIA Costs under Section 2.5, based on its revised Percentage Interest, which shall be based on such Project's revised Maximum Capacity as set forth on Exhibit B hereto. (b) The Maximum Capacity of any Project shall be decreased only upon receipt by such Project's Co-Tenant of written consent to such decrease provided by (i) CAISO and the Participating TO, and (ii) the other Co-Tenant, such consent not to be unreasonably withheld; provided however, that any such decrease in Maximum Capacity shall not decrease or change such Co-Tenant's responsibility for payment of Shared Expenses based on its initial Percentage Interest based on such Project's initial Maximum Capacity as set forth on Exhibit B hereto, including payment of LGIA Costs under Section 2.5. 2.7 Net Qualifying Capacity . Absent the prior written agreement of the Co-Tenants, and subject to the requirements and limitations of the CAISO Tariff, the aggregate Net Qualifying Capacity of the Projects shall not exceed 500 MWac and shall be allocated among the Projects in accordance with Exhibit C; provided, that, subject to the requirements and limitations of the CAISO Tariff, each Co-Tenant may transfer all or any portion of its Project's Net Qualifying Capacity to one or more Persons. 2.8 Indemnity . (a) Subject to the limitations provided in Section 7.11, each Co-Tenant (an "Indemnifying Co-Tenant") shall indemnify, defend and hold harmless the other Co-Tenant (an "Indemnified Co-Tenant") and the Manager from and against any and all losses, damages, liabilities, claims, judgments, liens, penalties, costs and expenses, including, without limitation, reasonable attorneys' and consultants' fees (collectively, "Claims"), which may be (i) imposed upon or incurred by such Indemnified Co-Tenant or Manager or asserted against such Indemnified Co-Tenant or Manager as a result of any breach by the Indemnifying Co-Tenant of this Agreement or the LGIA (including, without limitation, to the extent so imposed or incurred as the result of joint liability under the LGIA), or (ii) incurred by third parties in respect of loss of, or damage to, property or injury to, or death of, persons, as a result of negligence, fraud or willful misconduct of the Indemnifying Co-Tenant or in connection with the ownership, use, operation, maintenance or repair of the Indemnifying Co-Tenant's Project. (b) Subject to the limitations provided in Sections 3.3(c) and 7.11, the Manager shall indemnify, defend, and hold harmless the Co-Tenants from any Claims which may be (i) imposed upon or incurred by such Co-Tenants as a result of gross negligence, fraud or willful misconduct of the Manager, or (ii) incurred by third parties in respect of loss of, or damage to, property or injury to, or death of, persons, as a result of negligence, fraud or willful misconduct of the Manager. 2.9 Taxes . Each Co-Tenant shall pay all real and personal property taxes and assessments, general or special, levied against its Project, including any taxes and assessments levied against such Co-Tenant's Undivided Interest in the LGIA, except for any taxes or assessments that are LGIA Costs or that are paid pursuant to the Shared Facilities Agreement. All such taxes and assessments shall be paid before delinquency and before any fine, interest or penalty shall become due or be imposed for their non-payment; provided however, that each Co-Tenant retains its rights under applicable law to seek a refund of such taxes and assessments after having paid them. 2.10 Operation and Management; Insurance . (a) Each Co-Tenant shall operate and maintain its Project Controlled Assets acting as a prudent operator and manager and otherwise (i) in accordance with the terms of the LGIA, (ii) in accordance with Good Utility Practice, (iii) in compliance with all Applicable Laws and Regulations, including but not limited to the Federal Power Act, as amended ("FPA"), all rules, regulations, and orders issued by the FERC pursuant to the FPA, and all laws and regulations relating to land use, hazardous substances and environmental protection, (iv) in compliance with the CAISO Tariff, including the rules, protocols, procedures and standards attached thereto, as the same may be amended from time to time and approved by FERC, (v) in compliance with the rules, protocols, procedures and standards of NERC and WECC, and (f) without causing a material adverse effect on the LGIA. (b) Each Co-Tenant shall comply with its obligations under the LGIA, including with respect to its obligations to fund LGIA Costs arising under the LGIA. (c) Each Co-Tenant shall be an "exempt wholesale generator" as such term is defined in the Public Utility Holding Company Act of 2005. (d) Each Co-Tenant shall cooperate with and timely respond to the Manager as a representative for the Co-Tenants under the LGIA, and shall provide the Manager such information, certifications and other matters as may be required to comply with the obligations under the LGIA. (e) Each Co-Tenant shall maintain insurance in accordance with the requirements of the LGIA. The Manager shall maintain insurance in accordance with the requirements of Exhibit D hereto. 2.11 Joint and Several Liability . Notwithstanding any other provision hereof, each Co-Tenant acknowledges and agrees that under the LGIA it is jointly and severally liable for (i) any payments due under the LGIA imposed on the Interconnection Customer and (ii) the performance of the obligations and duties imposed on the Interconnection Customer by the LGIA; provided that a Co-Tenant's joint and several liability under the LGIA shall not diminish or impair any Co-Tenant's rights to reimbursement or contribution from another Co-Tenant or any other Person hereunder or under any other agreement, including the Shared Facilities Agreement. Each Co-Tenant hereby agrees to, promptly upon written request, reimburse, indemnify and hold harmless the other Co-Tenant for any cost, expense or liability incurred by such other Co-Tenant to the extent resulting from its joint liability under the LGIA for such first Co-Tenant's failure to make a payment when due or perform any other obligation or duty of such Co-Tenant under the LGIA. 2.12 Disconnection . The Manager shall have the power and authority to disconnect a Project from the Point of Interconnection (1) as provided in Section 5.2, (2) upon abandonment and decommissioning of a Co-Tenant's Project as provided in Section 4.2, (3) if necessary, consistent with Good Utility Practice for the operation and maintenance of any portion of the Interconnection Facilities, (4) if the Manager determines, in its good faith discretion, that disconnection is necessary in the event of an Emergency Condition or to otherwise prevent damage or injury to persons or property, including to the other Project, the Interconnection Facilities or the property of the Participating TO or as otherwise needed to prevent or mitigate technical issues affecting the Projects, provided that the Manager will use commercially reasonable efforts to give the Co-Tenants as much advance notice as is reasonably possible under the circumstances, consistent with responding to the Emergency Condition or preventing damage or injury to persons or property, or (5) at the direction of the Participating TO or the CAISO pursuant to rights under the LGIA. Unless Manager has in its good faith determined that it is unable to do so because an imminent threat of injury or death to persons, damage to property or default under the LGIA exists, Manager shall provide notice to the relevant Co-Tenant prior to or concurrently with disconnecting its Project or as soon thereafter as is reasonably practical. 2.13 Effect of Force Majeure . If a Party is unable to carry out its obligations under this Agreement because of an event of Force Majeure, and if such Party promptly gives the other Parties written notice of such Force Majeure in reasonable detail as soon as reasonably practicable, specifying (to the extent then known) the nature, extent and expected duration of such Force Majeure, the affected Party will be excused from the performance of its obligations hereunder to the extent such performance is prevented by such event of Force Majeure; provided that any Party affected by a Force Majeure shall diligently take all reasonable measures to mitigate or eliminate the effects of such event of Force Majeure; provided further that the suspension of a Party's performance hereunder due to Force Majeure shall be permitted solely for the duration of the effect of such Force Majeure and solely to the extent that the suspension of such Party's obligations does not cause a "Default" under the LGIA. ARTICLE III MANAGER 3.1 Appointment of Manager; Manager Services and Limitations . The Co-Tenants hereby appoint Oberon to serve as the Manager under the LGIA, subject to replacement as provided in Section 3.5 below, provided that, in accordance with the requirements of Appendix C, Section C.4(e) of the LGIA, Oberon in its role as Manager shall have no additional interest as an Interconnection Customer by virtue of its designation as Manager. The Manager is hereby authorized to act as the Co-Tenants' authorized agent and representative for all purposes under the LGIA (except as expressly stated herein), and, unless otherwise specifically agreed by the Co-Tenants or otherwise provided herein, the Manager shall have the power to exercise and shall exercise any and all of the rights of the Interconnection Customer under the LGIA and shall coordinate, administer and manage performance of the LGIA by the Co-Tenants. In addition, the Manager shall register with NERC as the "Generator Owner" of each of the Projects and be responsible for ensuring compliance with all applicable NERC and regional entity reliability standards applicable to the Projects. (a) Without limiting the generality of the foregoing, and subject to the limitations of authority of the Manager in Section 3.1(b) below, the Manager shall have the power, without further consent or approval of the Co-Tenants: (i) To send and receive requests, demands and other notices arising under or relating to the LGIA; (ii) To employ from time to time, at the expense of the Co-Tenants, persons, firms or corporations to render services generally needed to accomplish the purposes of the Co-Tenants with respect to the LGIA; provided that if the Manager retains any party who is an Affiliate of the Manager for any of these purposes, the fees charged shall be based on the lower of actual cost or fair market value; (iii) To pay and collect amounts due in connection with the LGIA, and to maintain one or more bank accounts wherein funds received by the Manager in connection with its duties hereunder shall be maintained; (iv) To expend monies necessary for the management and administration of the LGIA in accordance with Good Utility Practice, subject to the limitations contained herein; or (v) To execute, acknowledge, and deliver any and all instruments and take such other steps as are reasonably necessary to effectuate the foregoing and as are consistent therewith. (b) The Manager shall not without the prior, unanimous written consent of all of the Co-Tenants: (i) Create or cause to be created any lien on or security interest in the LGIA, terminate, amend or Transfer the LGIA or waive any material rights of the Co-Tenants thereunder, or initiate or settle any dispute under the LGIA; (ii) Amend or modify the terms of this Agreement, the LGIA or any other agreement to which the Co-Tenants are parties; (iii) Perform or omit to perform any act which would cause any person reasonably to believe that the Manager is authorized to bind such Co-Tenants, except as expressly provided herein, or which would cause any person reasonably to believe that the Manager is a partner of the Co-Tenant(s); (iv) Sell, assign, mortgage, encumber, convey or otherwise transfer all or any portion of any Undivided Interest; (v) Borrow funds on behalf of the Co-Tenants; (vi) Incur expenses, on behalf of the Co-Tenants, except in accordance with this Agreement and the LGIA; (vii) Settle any claim or resolve any dispute, including those with any regulatory agency, that has a value in excess of five thousand Dollars ($5,000) or that requires any contract or imposes a compliance plan on any Co-Tenant; or (viii) Enter into, on behalf of the Co-Tenants, any commitments, contracts or other agreements requiring expenditures in one year in excess of five thousand Dollars ($5,000) or with a duration of more than one (1) year. (c) Manager will be reimbursed for (i) all LGIA Costs described in clauses (i) and (ii) of the definition thereof, other than costs and charges that have already been paid to CAISO and the Participating TO under the LGIA or are separately paid by the Co-Tenants, and (ii) all costs and expenses incurred in acting as Manager (including reasonable actual costs of the employees of Manager's Affiliates, including reasonable administrative and general fees and other overhead charges) and not otherwise reimbursed pursuant to clause (i) above. Any Disputes regarding LGIA Costs or other costs and expenses shall be resolved pursuant to Section 5.4. 3.2 Communications . The Manager shall be the single point of contact between the Co-Tenants and CAISO and the Participating TO, and shall be responsible for all administrative obligations of the Interconnection Customer under the LGIA, including billing, issuing payments, providing notices and communicating with, and receiving instructions from, CAISO and the Participating TO with respect to the Projects and the LGIA. The Manager shall, promptly upon (and no later than one (1) calendar day following) receipt, provide to each Co-Tenant a copy of any notices or other material communications received by it under the LGIA. The Manager's actions and representations to CAISO and the Participating TO with respect to the LGIA shall be binding upon the Interconnection Customer and each individual Co-Tenant. Each Co-Tenant waives any right to individual notice or communication from CAISO or the Participating TO, and acknowledges that CAISO and the Participating TO will not be obligated to act on any instructions from a Co-Tenant, with respect to the LGIA. 3.3 Liability and Indemnification of Manager . (a) Each Co-Tenant shall, pro rata in accordance with its Percentage Interest, defend, indemnify and hold harmless the Manager and its employees and agents, from any claim, loss, liability or damage incurred by reason of any act performed or omitted to be performed by the Manager in its reasonable judgment, in good faith, or in reasonable reliance on advice of its attorneys or accountants, in connection with the LGIA or under this Agreement (other than for the Manager's own gross negligence, fraud or willful misconduct), including reasonable attorneys' fees incurred by the Manager in connection with the defense of any action based on any such alleged act or omission. The Co-Tenants agree that, so long as one of the Co-Tenants is the Manager, the foregoing indemnity means that the other Co-Tenant will only pay its pro rata share (in accordance with its Percentage Interest) of such indemnified claims, losses, liabilities and damages. (b) The Manager shall not be liable, responsible or accountable in damages or otherwise to any Co-Tenant for any act performed in good faith by the Manager in the discharge of its duties hereunder as the Manager or in the exercise of its powers and authority hereunder or under the LGIA as the Manager, including damages arising out of the disconnection of, or the election not to disconnect, a Co-Tenant's Project from the Point of Interconnection, unless the acts or omissions of the Manager constitute gross negligence, fraud, willful misconduct or an intentional breach of this Agreement. (c) In no event shall the Manager's liability under this Agreement (for the avoidance of doubt, in the event a Co-Tenant is the Manager, without prejudice to any liability of such Co-Tenant hereunder other than in respect of its capacity as Manager), whether based on contract, indemnity, warranty, or tort (other than liability arising out of the gross negligence, fraud or willful misconduct of the Manager) exceed the amount covered and received as insurance proceeds by the Manager under the applicable insurance policies obtained by the Parties hereunder, and provided further that the Manager's liability shall be reduced by any insurance proceeds received by the relevant Co-Tenants. In no event, whether based on contract, indemnity, warranty, tort or otherwise, shall Manager, or its agents, representatives or contractors, be liable for special, incidental, exemplary, indirect, or consequential damages, including loss of profits or revenue, cost of capital, or cost of purchased power, except for damages to third parties based on personal injury or property damage; provided, however, this Section 3.3 shall not be construed as a limitation or restriction on the amount or applicability of any insurance policies obtained by the Parties hereunder. 3.4 Books and Records; Reporting . (a) Maintenance or Records. The Manager shall maintain books and records in sufficient detail to verify amounts due and payable hereunder for a period of not less than three (3) years after the end of the calendar month to which they relate, or such longer period reasonably requested by a Co-Tenant, and all such books and records shall be available for inspection and/or copying by each Co-Tenant or its authorized representative at the cost and expense of such Co-Tenant and at reasonable times during regular business hours, upon reasonable notice to the Manager. (b) Provision of Records. The Manager shall, from time to time or at the reasonable request of a Co-Tenant (but not more often than once quarterly), provide reports to the Co-Tenants sufficient to keep the Co-Tenants reasonably apprised as to significant matters concerning the LGIA, the LGIA Costs, and any other amounts due under the LGIA or this Agreement. (c) Annual Statements. The Manager shall at the reasonable request of any Co-Tenant submit to the Co-Tenants an annual statement reconciling all amounts paid by each Co-Tenant during the preceding twelve (12) months against such Co-Tenant's share of all actual LGIA Costs and other amounts due from the Co-Tenants hereunder or from the Interconnection Customer under the LGIA during such twelve (12) month period, together with reasonable supporting documentation. If any Co-Tenant's share of such costs and expenses exceeds the amounts actually paid by such Co-Tenant, then such Co-Tenant shall promptly pay the amount of such difference to the Manager, who shall reimburse the other Co-Tenant, if and as applicable. If any Co-Tenant's share of such costs and expenses is less than the amounts actually paid by such Co-Tenant, then the Manager shall credit the amount of such overpayment by such Co-Tenant against future invoiced amounts from the Manager until such credit is exhausted. 3.5 Replacement of Manager . The Manager may only be removed upon the affirmative written direction of the Co-Tenants; provided, that the Manager shall also be removed upon the affirmative vote of all of the Co-Tenants (not including any Defaulting Party) following the occurrence and during the continuation of an Event of Default where the Manager is the Defaulting Party. Any replacement Manager must be approved by all of the Co-Tenants, except that the approval of a Co-Tenant that is a Defaulting Party is not required so long as the Event of Default is continuing and has not been cured. 3.6 No Discrimination . Except as otherwise provided in Sections 2.4 and 2.12, the Manager shall provide services and otherwise perform its obligations hereunder in a manner that treats each of the Co-Tenants alike under substantially similar conditions, except as required by Applicable Laws and Regulations or Good Utility Practice; for the avoidance of doubt, the Manager shall not exercise its authority under this Agreement in a manner that results in undue preference or discrimination with respect to any Co-Tenant other than as otherwise provided for herein. 3.7 Performance . The Manager shall perform its obligations under this Agreement in accordance with all Applicable Laws and Regulations, including the FPA, the CAISO Tariff and all applicable NERC standards, the terms of the LGIA, and Good Utility Practice. 3.8 Access Rights . Each Co-Tenant shall, upon reasonable notice from Manager, provide the Manager, its agents, representatives and contractors, with reasonable access to its Project in order for Manager to carry out its rights and obligations hereunder. All such activities shall be undertaken by the Manager, its agents, representatives and contractors, in accordance with each Co-Tenant's safety protocols and procedures as then in effect. 3.9 Contracting . The Manager may delegate the performance of or engage contractors to perform its obligations under this Agreement; provided that no delegation or contracting of services by Manager shall (i) relieve Manager of its obligations or liabilities hereunder, (ii) relieve Manager of its responsibility for the completion of performance of any services rendered by any such delegate or contractor or (iii) create any relationship between the Co-Tenants, on the one hand, and any delegate or contractor, on the other. In addition, Manager shall cause each of its delegates and contractors to comply with the Manager's obligations under this Agreement to the extent applicable to such delegate's or contractor's work, including maintaining all necessary insurance not otherwise provided by the Manager. ARTICLE IV TERM 4.1 Term . The term of this Agreement will commence on the Effective Date and will terminate on the earliest of the unanimous written agreement by CAISO, the Participating TO and the Co-Tenants to (i) terminate this Agreement, provided, however, that termination in such event shall not cause a default under the LGIA, (ii) the consolidation of interest in the LGIA in a single Person, or (iii) termination of the LGIA with respect to one, but not all of the Projects. The provisions of Sections 2.7, 2.10 and 3.3 will survive termination of this Agreement. 4.2 Surrender and Assignment of Undivided Interest . A Co-Tenant who wishes to abandon and decommission its Project may, subject to the agreement of the other Co-Tenant (at its sole discretion), elect to convey its Undivided Interest and assign its rights hereunder to the other Co-Tenant and thereupon to cease to have any right, title or interest in the LGIA (such Co-Tenant, a "Surrendering Co-Tenant"). The Surrendering Co-Tenant must (a) deliver all instruments of transfer as may be necessary or appropriate to effect the conveyance of its Undivided Interest and assignment of its rights hereunder to, and which are reasonably satisfactory to, the remaining Co-Tenant, (b) assign and convey to the remaining Co-Tenant all its rights under this Agreement, free and clear of any liens, security interests or other encumbrances, provided, however, that any such surrender of an encumbered Undivided Interest may only be surrendered with the written consent of each Financing Party that holds a security interest in such Undivided Interest and a release of such Financing Party's security interest, (c) obtain all necessary consents and approvals under all Applicable Laws and Regulations prior to any such assignment, at the Surrendering Co-Tenant's sole cost and expense, (d) obtain all necessary consents and approvals under the LGIA prior to any such assignment, at the Surrendering Co-Tenant's sole cost and expense; and (e) cure all Events of Default then existing on the part of the Surrendering Co-Tenant. The Surrendering Co-Tenant shall remain fully responsible for, and shall pay all costs of obtaining the consents and approvals and of surrendering its Undivided Interest as described above. No surrender of a Co-Tenant's Undivided Interest shall relieve the Surrendering Party of any of its obligations (including but not limited to payment obligations due and payable through the effective date of its surrender of its Undivided Interest) under this Agreement, its real property rights or any other agreement entered into pursuant to this Agreement, unless expressly provided for in this Agreement, or in a writing between the Parties. ARTICLE V DEFAULT AND REMEDIES 5.1 Events of Default; Default . The following shall each constitute a default by a Party (the "Defaulting Party") under this Agreement (each an "Event of Default"): (a) a Party fails to make any payment when due under this Agreement and such Party fails to cure such default within ten (10) days ("Payment Default Cure Period") after receipt of written notice of such default; (b) a Party fails to perform any other covenant or obligation under this Agreement in any material respect, and such Party fails to cure such failure within thirty (30) days ("General Default Cure Period") after receipt of written notice of such default, provided if the nature of the defaulted obligation is such that more than thirty (30) days are reasonably required to cure such default, then the General Default Cure Period for such Event of Default shall be extended by such additional time, not to exceed ninety (90) days in total after receipt of the written notice of default, as is reasonably necessary to cure such default, provided such Party commences to cure such default promptly, and in all events within thirty (30) days after receiving notice of such default, and thereafter diligently pursues such cure to completion; (c) a Default (as defined in the LGIA) occurs as a result of the actions or inactions of such Party (for the avoidance of doubt, after giving effect to any cure periods provided in the LGIA in respect of the underlying Breach (as defined in the LGIA)); or (d) a Bankruptcy Event occurs with respect to such Party. 5.2 Remedies . (a) Following and during the continuation of an Event of Default by a Co-Tenant, the other Co-Tenant shall have the following remedies, exercisable in its sole discretion, but only after the expiration of the Payment Default Cure Period or General Default Cure Period, as applicable, if the Event of Default occurs under Sections 5.1(a) or (b): (i) To cure the default of the defaulting Co-Tenant by making or tendering the required payment or performance, and permitting the defaulting Co-Tenant's Project to continue to exercise its rights under the LGIA, provided that any such amounts paid by the non-defaulting Co-Tenant shall be treated as a loan to the defaulting Co-Tenant, which loan shall accrue interest until repaid in full at the Interest Rate; (ii) To bring an action for money damages or other appropriate relief; (iii) To bring an action to specifically enforce the provisions of this Agreement; (iv) To demand disconnection of the defaulting Co-Tenant's Project in accordance with Section 2.11 hereof, provided, that (A) the Manager shall have in good faith determined that bringing an action for money damages and/or for specific performance will not provide an adequate or timely remedy for such default (or, in the event that the defaulting Co-Tenant is the Manager, the Manager's determination under this Section 5.2(a)(iv)(A) shall not be required), (B) the defaulting Co-Tenant's Project shall be permitted to reconnect promptly when and if the default is cured, and (C) in the case of any such reconnection, the non-defaulting Co-Tenant and the Manager shall have been compensated in full for any and all costs and damage they incurred, respectively (or, in the event the non-defaulting Co-Tenant is the Manager, that it incurred in its capacities as Co-Tenant and as Manager), as a result of such Event of Default; and/or (v) To suspend the rights of the defaulting Co-Tenant under this Agreement (including, without limitation, any rights of the defaulting Co-Tenant under this Agreement to receive any reimbursement or compensation under this Agreement, including, without limitation, pursuant to Section 2.7, except to the extent required pursuant to applicable law), including if applicable its rights as Manager, until the Event of Default has been cured; provided that no such suspension shall be deemed to suspend or otherwise affect the obligations of the defaulting Co-Tenant (including, without limitation and as applicable, in its capacity as Manager) under this Agreement. For the avoidance of doubt, during any such suspension, the defaulting Co-Tenant shall have no, and shall not be entitled to enforce any, rights under this Agreement (including, without limitation and as applicable, in its capacity as Manager); and/or (vi) To exercise any and all other rights and remedies which the non-defaulting Co-Tenant might otherwise have at law or in equity. (b) Following and during the continuation of an Event of Default by the Manager, any Co-Tenant (not including any Defaulting Party) shall have the following remedies, exercisable in their sole discretion, but only after the expiration of the Payment Default Cure Period or General Default Cure Period, as applicable, if the Event of Default occurs under Sections 5.1(a) or (b): (i) To remove the Manager, as provided by Section 3.5 (without limiting the provisions thereof); (ii) To cure the default of the Manager, provided any amounts paid shall be recoverable from the Manager, subject to the limitations of liability set forth in Section 3.3(c); (iii) To bring an action for money damages or other appropriate relief; (iv) To bring an action to specifically enforce the provisions of this Agreement; and/or (v) To exercise any and all other rights and remedies which they might otherwise have at law or in equity. 5.3 Equitable Relief . The Parties agree that damages may be an inadequate remedy for certain Events of Default, and that each Party shall be entitled to seek injunctive and other equitable relief, including specific performance, against any other Party or the Manager to prevent or eliminate such Event of Default. 5.4 Dispute Resolution . (a) Any controversy, claim or dispute between the Co-Tenants (including with the Co-Tenant acting as the Manager hereunder in its capacity as the Manager) arising out of or related to this Agreement or the breach thereof, or regarding the application or interpretation of any provision of this Agreement, that cannot be settled amicably by the Co-Tenants (a "Dispute") will be submitted first to mediation, and if mediation fails to achieve a resolution within a time period reasonably acceptable to the Co-Tenant alleging the Dispute, then for binding arbitration by a three-member arbitration panel in accordance with the provisions contained herein and the Commercial Arbitration Rules of the American Arbitration Association (the "Arbitration Rules"). In arbitration, the Co-Tenants will be permitted to conduct reasonable discovery in accordance with the Federal Rules of Civil Procedure, and the Arbitration Rules will be deemed to include Fed. R. Civ. P. 26(b), 30, 31, 33, 34, and 36. The Co-Tenants will share equally in the fees and expenses of the arbitration panel. Judgment upon the award rendered by the arbitration panel may be entered in any court having jurisdiction. The arbitration panel will determine all questions of fact and law relating to any Dispute hereunder, including whether or not any such Dispute hereunder is subject to the arbitration provisions contained herein. (b) Any Co-Tenant desiring arbitration under this Section 5.4 (the "Demanding Party") will serve on the other Co-Tenant, and the Office of the American Arbitration Association in San Francisco, California, in accordance with the Rules, its demand for arbitration (the "Demand"), accompanied by the name of the person chosen by the Demanding Party to select an arbitrator with experience in the subject matter of the relevant Dispute. The responding Co-Tenant will choose a second person to select an arbitrator with experience in the subject matter of the relevant Dispute, and the two persons so chosen will select the arbitration panel. All of the arbitrators will be independent and neutral. If the two persons chosen by the Parties cannot agree upon a three-member arbitration panel within thirty (30) days after the designation of the second person, then each such person may select one independent and neutral arbitrator, and the two arbitrators so selected will select a third independent and neutral arbitrator, who will serve as the panel chair. If the responding Co-Tenant upon whom the Demand is served fails to advise the Demanding Party of its choice of a person to select the arbitration panel within fifteen (15) days after receipt of the Demand, or if the foregoing arbitration selection procedure fails for any other reason, the arbitrators will be selected in accordance with the Arbitration Rules. The arbitration proceedings provided hereunder are hereby declared to be self-executing, and it will not be necessary to petition a court to compel arbitration. All arbitration proceedings will be held in San Francisco, California. (c) Notice of the Demand will be filed in writing with the other Co-Tenant and with the American Arbitration Association. The Demand will be made within a reasonable time after the claim, Dispute or other matter in question has arisen, and in no event will it be made after the date when institution or legal or equitable proceedings based on such claim, Dispute or other matter in question would be barred by the applicable statutes of limitations. (d) Notwithstanding the foregoing, (i) the Co-Tenants may at any time seek injunctive relief from a court of competent jurisdiction, and (ii) nothing herein will prevent a Co-Tenant from defending or pursuing any claim in a court or other proceeding against a third party that has been initiated by such third party. In the event any Dispute involves common issues of fact, liability or responsibility with any dispute or controversy under any other agreement (including power purchase agreements, interconnection agreements and other project agreements), each of the Co-Tenants agrees, where reasonably justified, to join such disputes and controversies to seek a common resolution of all such matters. 5.5 Notice of Default . Each Co-Tenant and the Manager shall promptly (and in any event within two (2) Business Days) provide written notice to the other Parties upon receiving notice of, or otherwise discovering, any default or potential default under this Agreement or the LGIA or receiving any other notice under the LGIA. ARTICLE VI TRANSFERABILITY 6.1 General Restriction and Obligation . No Party may Transfer all or any part of its rights and obligations under this Agreement to any another Person without the written consent of the other Parties (such consent not to be unreasonably withheld, delayed or conditioned); provided that (i) a Co-Tenant may, without the written consent of the other Parties, Transfer all, but not less than all, of its Undivided Interest and other rights under this Agreement to (A) a Person to whom it is Transferring all, but not less than all, of its interest in its Project and Project Controlled Assets, so long as such Person has demonstrated to the other Co-Tenant's reasonable satisfaction that it has, either directly, through an Affiliate or by contract, sufficient financial capacity and technical ability to perform its obligations under this Agreement, or (B) an Affiliate of the assigning Co-Tenant that succeeds to all of such assigning Co-Tenant's interests in its Project and Project Controlled Assets, but in each case only if the Transferee assumes in writing all of the Transferring Co-Tenant's duties, obligations and liabilities hereunder and with respect to the LGIA, and (ii) a Co-Tenant may encumber its Undivided Interest for financing purposes as provided below without the consent of the other Co-Tenant. No Transfer may occur unless all necessary consents and approvals under all Applicable Laws and Regulations and the LGIA have been obtained prior to such Transfer. In the event a Party wishes to Transfer its Undivided Interest pursuant to clauses (i) or (ii) above, it shall give the other Parties written notice of such intent, including copies of all instruments of Transfer, assumption agreements, consents and approvals, not less than thirty (30) days before effecting any such Transfer. Without prejudice to Section 6.2(a) below, all Transfers in violation of the foregoing are void. 6.2 Co-Tenant's Right to Encumber . (a) Pledge, Collateral Assignment or Encumbrance. Each Party specifically agrees that, without obtaining the consent of the other Parties, (i) any Co-Tenant may at any time pledge, collaterally assign, encumber, grant a security interest in, or, in the case of a lease financing, assign, its Undivided Interest in its rights under this Agreement and the LGIA to any Financing Party concurrently with pledging, collaterally assigning, encumbering or granting a security interest in such Co-Tenant's Project to such Financing Party, provided such Co-Tenant has first obtained all necessary consents and approvals under all Applicable Laws and Regulations and the LGIA, if any; and (ii) any Financing Party may exercise its rights under its agreement with such Co-Tenant, including foreclosing, receiving, Transferring, conveying or assigning such pledged Undivided Interest; provided that such Financing Party first complies with all requirements under the LGIA and all Applicable Laws and Regulations and promptly cures all Events of Default by such Co-Tenant under Sections 5.1(a) and (b) which are capable of being cured without possession of the applicable Project after exercising such rights. Notwithstanding the foregoing, any pledge, collateral assignment or encumbrance of, or grant of a security interest in, any Co-Tenant's interest in this Agreement must include a similar pledge, collateral assignment or encumbrance of, or grant of a security interest in such Co-Tenant's interest in the LGIA. (b) Financing Parties. Should a Co-Tenant pledge, collaterally assign, encumber, grant a security interest in or assign its Undivided Interest and its rights in the LGIA as provided in Section 6.2(a) above, the Parties expressly agree between themselves and for the benefit of any Financing Party that (i) to the extent an amendment of this Agreement requires the assigning Co-Tenant's consent, no such amendment shall be implemented unless the consent of such Co-Tenant's Financing Parties of which the other Parties have received written notice is first obtained, (ii) upon the occurrence of an Event of Default by the assigning Co-Tenant, the non-defaulting Co-Tenant declaring the Event of Default shall also provide written notice of such Event of Default to the representative or agent of the Financing Parties in respect of which the assigning Co-Tenant has given the non-defaulting Co-Tenant written notice as provided below and accept such Financing Parties' cure (if any) of such Event of Default, (iii) each Financing Party shall have the same period after receipt of a notice of Event of Default to cure, or cause to be cured, the Event of Default described therein, as is given to the defaulting Co-Tenant hereunder, except that (A) the Payment Default Cure Period shall be thirty (30) days, and (B) the General Default Cure Period shall be sixty (60) days and may be extended to up to one hundred twenty (120) days in the aggregate under the conditions specified in Section 5.1(b), and (iv) if this Agreement or a Co-Tenant's interest in this Agreement is terminated or rejected as a result of a Bankruptcy Event of such Co-Tenant, the other Parties shall, upon written request of such defaulting Co-Tenant's Financing Party made within forty-five (45) days after the termination or rejection of this Agreement or the relevant Co-Tenant's interest therein, enter into a new Co-Tenancy Agreement with such Financing Party, on the same terms and conditions as this Agreement, or to the extent only the relevant Co-Tenant's interest is terminated or rejected, permit such Financing Party to join in this Agreement as a new Co-Tenant in place of the relevant Co-Tenant. Upon the execution of any such new Co-Tenancy Agreement, unless otherwise prohibited by a bankruptcy court order or by law, the Financing Party shall pay any amounts owed by the relevant Co-Tenant to the Manager or the other Co-Tenant under this Agreement and cure any Events of Default by the relevant Co-Tenant under this Agreement to the extent they can be cured. The non-defaulting Co-Tenant shall not be required to provide notice as provided in clause (ii) above unless the assigning Co-Tenant has, prior to the occurrence of the relevant underlying default, provided the non-defaulting Co-Tenant written notice providing such Co-Tenant with the name of a contact person, address, telephone, facsimile number and email address for a single representative or agent of the Financing Parties of such assigning Co-Tenant designated to receive such notices. (c) Estoppels and Consents. In connection with the financing of each Project, each Party will, upon the reasonable request of the Project owner and at such Project owner's cost and expense, provide customary estoppels and consents in favor of the applicable Financing Parties; provided that no Party shall be under any obligation to make any modifications to this Agreement or to incur any additional obligations under any such consent or estoppel. Article 3
PAYMENT OF O&M EXPENSES 3.1 Expenses of Operation and Maintenance of the Shared Facilities and Shared Premises. The Operation and Maintenance of the Shared Facilities and Shared Premises shall be performed in accordance with the requirements set forth in Article 5 below. The expenses of such Operation and Maintenance shall be allocated among the Project Companies and paid as provided in this Article 3. (a) Shared O&M Expenses. Each Project Company with a Proportionate Share that is a member of a Shared Assets Group shall be responsible for and shall pay its Proportionate Share of the expenses and liabilities relating to the Operation and Maintenance of such Shared Assets Group, including all allocable payments under the O&M Agreement and agreements for telecom services and electric distribution service for the Shared Facilities, all FERC compliance costs, NERC compliance costs, costs of compliance with other Governmental Requirements, costs of labor and materials and accounting, general and administrative costs (collectively, Shared O&M Expenses). Where possible, Shared O&M Expenses shall be allocated to the Shared Assets Group for which such Shared O&M Expenses were incurred. If it is not reasonable to allocate such Shared O&M Expenses, they shall be allocated to the All Projects Shared Assets Group. (b) Step-In Rights; Indemnity. If any Project Company fails to pay its share of Shared O&M Expenses as and when due, including any amounts that may be due to the Manager hereunder, then, upon at least five (5) days written notice to the defaulting Project Company, any other Project Company may, but shall not be obligated to, advance any amounts which such defaulting Project Company failed to pay, and such defaulting Project Company shall promptly reimburse the Project Company or Project Companies making such advances upon demand for all such amounts advanced on behalf of the defaulting Project Company, together with interest thereon from the date advanced to the date repaid at the Default Interest Rate. 3.2 Invoicing, Late Payments. (a) The Manager shall be responsible for invoicing each Project Company for its applicable Proportionate Share of the Shared O&M Expenses relating to the Shared Facilities Group of which it is a member. Each such invoice shall be payable by the invoiced Project Company within fifteen (15) days after receipt of an invoice, with backup documentation, from the Manager setting forth the amount that is due. If a Project Company disputes the invoiced amount, it shall nonetheless pay the disputed amount, and shall refer the issue for resolution in accordance with the provisions of Article 13. Any disputed amount that is finally determined by dispute resolution pursuant to Article 13 or by mutual agreement to have been improperly invoiced shall be promptly refunded to the Project Company. All sums not paid when due shall thereafter bear interest at the Default Interest Rate. Each Project Company shall have the right to audit, and 12 4132-4551-0705.14
receive supporting documentation for, any expenses or other amounts required to be paid by such Project Company hereunder. (b) In addition to the reports under Section 5.7, within thirty (30) days after the end of each calendar year, the Manager shall provide the Project Companies an annual statement of all actual Shared O&M Expenses during the previous calendar year, all payments made by each Project Company on account of Shared O&M Expenses, and a reconciliation of the amounts paid by each such Project Company against such Project Companys Proportionate Share of the actual Shared O&M Expenses (by Shared Assets Group) during such calendar year. Article 7
INSURANCE 7.1 Property Insurance. The Manager shall maintain liability insurance, including general liability coverage, covering the Shared Premises and the Shared Facilities, and each Project Company shall maintain liability insurance covering its Project and Property for any activities on the site of its Project or the Shared Premises. Each Party shall obtain and maintain commercial general liability insurance covering liability for bodily injury and death, and property damage to third parties, including loss of use thereof. Such coverage shall have a minimum limit of not less than Five Million Dollars ($5,000,000) per occurrence and Five Million Dollars ($5,000,000) 28 4132-4551-0705.14
annual aggregate for bodily injury and property damage, provided that such coverage (i) may be provided as part of a blanket policy covering other properties and may be provided by a combination of primary and excess policies, (ii) shall contain a blanket broad form contractual endorsement and severability of interest clause, and (iii) shall designate the Parties, the Secured Parties, and their officers, directors, employees and agents as additional insureds. If a policy described above is on a claims made basis, the retroactive date of the policy shall be on or before the Agreement Date. In the event of a casualty that affects any of the Shared Facilities, all insurance proceeds with respect to the Shared Facilities shall be applied to reconstruction of the affected Shared Facilities. If there is uninsured loss or insurance proceeds are inadequate, the Parties shall contribute additional amounts based on their Proportionate Shares in the affected Shared Asset Group; provided that amounts due with respect to any claims arising from the gross negligence or willful misconduct of a Party shall be first fully allocated to the account of such Party and then any balance not arising from the gross negligence or willful misconduct of such Party being contributed by the Parties based on their Proportionate Shares in the affected Shared Asset Group. In the event of any liability claim relating to any of the Shared Premises or Shared Facilities, to the extent such claim is not covered by the insurance required pursuant to this Article 7, the Parties shall be responsible for such claim based on their Proportionate Shares in the affected Shared Asset Group; provided that amounts due with respect to any claims arising from the gross negligence or willful misconduct of a Party shall be first fully allocated to the account of such Party and then any balance not arising from the gross negligence or willful misconduct of such Party being contributed by the Parties based on their Proportionate Shares. 7.7 Form and Content of Insurance. All policies and binders with respect to insurance provided pursuant to this Article 7 shall be as follows: (a) Form of Policies. All insurance provided for hereunder shall be placed on forms reasonably acceptable to the Parties and the Secured Parties. (b) Insurance Companies. All insurance required hereunder shall be with insurers with an A.M. Best rating of A-VII or better or with insurers otherwise deemed acceptable to the Parties, and the Secured Parties (acting reasonably). 29 4132-4551-0705.14
(c) Severability. All liability insurance shall contain a severability of interest provision providing that, except with respect to the total limits of liability, the insurance shall apply to each insured or additional insured in the same manner as if separate policies had been issued to each. commercial general liability insurance, automobile liability insurance and employers liability insurance in the amount of at least Five Million Dollars ($5,000,000) per occurrence and in the aggregate which may be provided through a combination of primary and excess (umbrella) liability insurance policies and workers compensation insurance as required by law, (ii) include Manager and each Project Company as additional insureds for ongoing and completed operations, (iii) include a waiver of subrogation in favour of Manager and each Project Company, and (iv) furnish the Manager with certificates of such insurance, prior to entry on the Shared Premises and during the time in which they are engaged in performing any services. All premiums for insurance obtained by the Manager shall be considered Shared O&M Expenses for purposes of this Agreement and shall be allocated to the appropriate Shared Asset Group(s). 7.9 Limitation on Insurance Requirements. (a) Notwithstanding anything in this Article 7 to the contrary, if insurance meeting the requirements set forth herein is not available on commercially reasonable terms, then the Manager shall obtain such insurance on terms in accordance with the requirements of this Article 7 to the extent, if any, such insurance is available on commercially reasonable terms, as certified by the Manager to the Parties. Company hereunder, the non-defaulting Party declaring the default shall also provide written notice to the defaulting Partys Secured Parties of such default (and accept their cure of such default on the terms set forth herein), (iii) each such Secured Party shall have the same period after receipt of a notice of default to cure, or cause to be cured, the default described therein, as is given to the defaulting Party, plus, in each instance, any additional cure periods provided under the Security Documents, not to exceed (a) thirty (30) days in the event of any monetary default; and (b) sixty (60) days in the event of any non-monetary default; provided, however, that such sixty (60)-day period shall be extended for the time reasonably required by the Secured Party to complete such cure (not to exceed one hundred twenty (120) days in the aggregate), so long as the Secured Party is diligently pursuing such cure, and (iv) in case of the bankruptcy, insolvency or appointment of a receiver in bankruptcy for a Project Company (the Insolvent Party), if this Agreement is terminated with respect to the Insolvent Party or rejected in such proceeding, the other Parties (the Solvent Parties) shall upon written request of the first priority Secured Party of the Insolvent Party, within thirty (30) days after the Secured Party obtains possession or control of the assets of the Insolvent Party, accept such Secured Party, or its designee or assignee, as a Party to this Agreement or enter into a new shared facilities agreement with respect to the Shared Facilities with such Secured Party, or its designee or assignee, within twenty (20) days after the receipt of such request. Shared Facilities.
